<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-09-14T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-09-14T00:00:00-05:00" n="1514" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1514">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 817.51/499.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Minister</gloss> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi>.</head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Managua</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-09-14">
                                    <hi rend="italic">September 14, 1912</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>There is urgent need of money to pay troops and meet other legitimate
                            expenses necessarily incurred in putting down disorders. But recourse to
                            internal loans would be decidedly unpopular and inadvisable. Therefore I
                            strongly recommend that bankers advance additional sums on equitable
                            terms for at least three months, during which normal conditions will
                            probably be established.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Weitzel.</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>